0:34.name: Parser
0:34.docs:
The parser structure for interpreting the input format string. This is
modeled as an iterator over `Piece` structures to form a stream of tokens
being output.

This is a recursive-descent parser for the sake of simplicity, and if
necessary there's probably lots of room for improvement performance-wise.

0:41.name: style
0:41.docs: `Some(raw count)` when the string is "raw", used to position spans correctly

0:86.name: count
0:86.docs:
Parses a `Count` parameter at the current position. This does not check
for 'CountIsNextParam' because that is only used in precision, not
width.

0:67.name: must_consume
0:67.docs:
Forces consumption of the specified character. If the character is not
found, an error is emitted.

0:198.name: Alignment
0:198.docs: Enum of alignments which are supported.

0:158.name: flags
0:158.docs: Packed version of various flags provided.

0:64.name: consume_pos
0:64.docs:
Optionally consumes the specified character. If the character is not at
the current position, then the current iterator isn't moved and `None` is
returned, otherwise the character is consumed and the current position is
returned.

0:70.name: ws
0:70.docs: Consumes all whitespace characters until the first non-whitespace character

0:73.name: position
0:73.docs:
Parses a positional argument for a format. This could either be an
integer index of an argument, a named argument, or a blank string.
Returns `Some(parsed_position)` if the position is not implicitly
consuming a macro argument, `None` if it's the case.

0:88.name: integer
0:88.docs:
Optionally parses an integer at the current position. This doesn't deal
with overflow at all, it's just accumulating digits.

0:43.name: skips
0:43.docs: Characters that need to be shifted

0:215.name: Flag
0:215.docs:
Various flags which can be applied to format strings. The meaning of these
flags is defined by the formatters themselves.

0:183.name: ArgumentIs
0:183.docs: The argument is located at a specific index given in the format

0:218.name: FlagSignMinus
0:218.docs: A `-` will be used to denote negative numbers. This is the default.

0:199.name: AlignLeft
0:199.docs: The value will be aligned to the left.

0:80.name: inline_asm
0:80.docs:
Parses an inline assembly template modifier at the current position, returning the modifier
in the `ty` field of the `FormatSpec` struct.

0:161.name: width
0:161.docs: The string width requested for the resulting format.

0:222.name: FlagSignAwareZeroPad
0:222.docs:
For numbers, this means that the number will be padded with zeroes,
and the sign (`+` or `-`) will precede them.

0:56.name: err
0:56.docs:
Notifies of an error. The message doesn't actually need to be of type
String, but I think it does when this eventually uses conditions so it
might as well start using it now.

0:162.name: width_span
0:162.docs: The span of the width formatting flag (for diagnostics).

0:164.name: ty_span
0:164.docs: The span of the descriptor string (for diagnostics).

0:224.name: FlagDebugLowerHex
0:224.docs: For Debug / `?`, format integers in lower-case hexadecimal.

0:216.name: FlagSignPlus
0:216.docs: A `+` will be used to denote positive numbers.

0:0.name: rustc_parse_format
0:0.docs:
Macro support for format strings

These structures are used when parsing format strings for the compiler.
Parsing does not happen at runtime: structures of `std::fmt::rt` are
generated instead.

0:156.name: fill
0:156.docs: Optionally specified character to fill alignment with.

0:179.name: Position
0:179.docs: Enum describing where an argument for a format can be located.

0:236.name: Count
0:236.docs:
A count is used for the precision and width parameters of an integer, and
can reference either an argument or a literal integer.

0:87.name: word
0:87.docs:
Parses a word starting at the current position. A word is the same as
Rust identifier, except that it can't start with `_` character.

0:74.name: format
0:74.docs:
Parses a format specifier at the current position, returning all of the
relevant information in the `FormatSpec` struct.

0:220.name: FlagAlternate
0:220.docs:
An alternate form will be used for the value. In the case of numbers,
this means that the number will be prefixed with the supplied string.

0:163.name: ty
0:163.docs:
The descriptor string representing the name of the format desired for
this argument, this can be empty or any number of characters, although
it is required to be one word.

0:240.name: CountIsName
0:240.docs: The count is specified by the argument with the given name.

0:44.name: last_opening_brace
0:44.docs: Span of the last opening brace seen, used for error reporting

0:42.name: arg_places
0:42.docs: Start and end byte offset of every successfully parsed argument

0:55.name: new
0:55.docs: Creates a new parser for the given format string

0:40.name: curarg
0:40.docs: Current position of implicit positional argument pointer

0:46.name: is_literal
0:46.docs: Whether this formatting string is a literal or it comes from a macro.

0:72.name: argument
0:72.docs: Parses an `Argument` structure, or what's contained within braces inside the format string.

0:45.name: append_newline
0:45.docs: Whether the source string is comes from `println!` as opposed to `format!` or `print!`

0:114.name: Piece
0:114.docs:
A piece is a portion of the format string which represents the next part
to emit. These are emitted as a stream by the `Parser` class.

0:119.name: NextArgument
0:119.docs:
This describes that formatting should process the next argument (as
specified inside) for emission.

0:201.name: AlignRight
0:201.docs: The value will be aligned to the right.

0:95.name: InlineAsm
0:95.docs: An inline assembly template string for `asm!`.

0:154.name: FormatSpec
0:154.docs: Specification for the formatting of an argument in the format string.

0:243.name: CountIsParam
0:243.docs: The count is specified by the argument at the given index.

0:63.name: consume
0:63.docs:
Optionally consumes the specified character. If the character is not at
the current position, then the current iterator isn't moved and `false` is
returned, otherwise the character is consumed and `true` is returned.

0:246.name: CountImplied
0:246.docs: The count is implied and cannot be explicitly specified.

0:71.name: string
0:71.docs:
Parses all of a string which is to be considered a "raw literal" in a
format string. This is everything outside of the braces.

0:59.name: err_with_note
0:59.docs:
Notifies of an error. The message doesn't actually need to be of type
String, but I think it does when this eventually uses conditions so it
might as well start using it now.

0:92.name: ParseMode
0:92.docs: The type of format string that we are parsing.

0:205.name: AlignUnknown
0:205.docs: The value will take on a default alignment.

0:226.name: FlagDebugUpperHex
0:226.docs: For Debug / `?`, format integers in upper-case hexadecimal.

0:160.name: precision_span
0:160.docs: The span of the precision formatting flag (for diagnostics).

0:89.name: find_skips_from_snippet
0:89.docs:
Finds the indices of all characters that have been processed and differ between the actual
written code (code snippet) and the `InternedString` that gets processed in the `Parser`
in order to properly synthethise the intra-string `Span`s for error diagnostics.

0:48.name: line_spans
0:48.docs:
Start and end byte offset of every line of the format string. Excludes
newline characters and leading whitespace.

0:47.name: cur_line_start
0:47.docs: Start position of the current line.

0:180.name: ArgumentImplicitlyIs
0:180.docs: The argument is implied to be located at an index

0:116.name: String
0:116.docs: A literal string which should directly be emitted

0:93.name: Format
0:93.docs: A normal format string as per `format_args!`.

0:203.name: AlignCenter
0:203.docs: The value will be aligned in the center.
